<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Career Practice Journal</title>
<style>
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Fraunces:opsz,wght@9..144,500;9..144,600;9..144,700&family=Inter:wght@400;500;600;700&family=IBM+Plex+Mono:wght@400;500&display=swap');

:root{
  --bg:#FBF8F1;
  --panel:#FFFFFF;
  --panel-2:#F3EEE0;
  --border:#E4DCC8;
  --ink:#1B2340;
  --ink-dim:#5B6178;
  --accent:#4F46E5;
  --accent-2:#EEEDFE;
  --teal:#0D7A66;
  --danger:#C1443A;
  --danger-bg:#FBE2DE;
  --shadow-sm:0 2px 8px -3px rgba(27,35,64,0.12);
  --shadow:0 10px 26px -10px rgba(27,35,64,0.2);
  --radius:14px;
  --radius-sm:10px;
}
*{box-sizing:border-box;}
body{margin:0;background:var(--bg);color:var(--ink);font-family:'Inter',sans-serif;min-height:100vh;font-size:18px;-webkit-font-smoothing:antialiased;}
#app{max-width:800px;margin:0 auto;padding:26px 24px 100px;}

.eyebrow{font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:12.5px;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--accent);margin:0 0 10px;font-weight:600;}
h1,h2,h3{font-family:'Fraunces',serif;margin:0;font-weight:700;color:var(--ink);letter-spacing:-.01em;}
h1{font-size:32px;line-height:1.2;}
h2{font-size:24px;}
p{line-height:1.75;font-size:18px;}

.btn{font-family:'Inter',sans-serif;font-size:15px;font-weight:600;border:1.5px solid var(--border);background:var(--panel);color:var(--ink);padding:12px 20px;border-radius:var(--radius-sm);cursor:pointer;transition:border-color .15s, transform .1s;box-shadow:var(--shadow-sm);}
.btn:hover{border-color:var(--accent);}
.btn:focus-visible{outline:2px solid var(--accent);outline-offset:2px;}
.btn-primary{background:var(--accent);color:#fff;border:none;}
.btn-primary:hover{background:#4038c9;}
.btn-danger{background:var(--danger);color:#fff;border:none;}
.btn-ghost{background:transparent;box-shadow:none;}
.btn-sm{padding:7px 12px;font-size:13px;}
.btn-row{display:flex;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-top:20px;}

.screen{animation:fade .2s ease;}
@keyframes fade{from{opacity:0;transform:translateY(6px);}to{opacity:1;transform:translateY(0);}}

.center-stage{min-height:72vh;display:flex;flex-direction:column;align-items:center;justify-content:center;text-align:center;gap:26px;}
.lang-card-row{display:flex;gap:16px;flex-wrap:wrap;justify-content:center;}
.lang-card{padding:22px 40px;border-radius:var(--radius);border:2px solid var(--border);background:var(--panel);font-weight:700;font-size:18px;cursor:pointer;box-shadow:var(--shadow-sm);transition:border-color .15s, transform .1s;}
.lang-card:hover{border-color:var(--accent);transform:translateY(-2px);}

.menu-card{width:100%;text-align:left;padding:24px 24px;background:var(--panel);border:1.5px solid var(--border);border-left:4px solid var(--accent);border-radius:var(--radius);cursor:pointer;margin-bottom:14px;box-shadow:var(--shadow-sm);transition:transform .12s;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:16px;}
.menu-card:hover{transform:translateX(2px);}
.menu-card p:last-child{color:var(--ink-dim);margin:0;font-size:15.5px;}
.menu-card .arrow{font-size:20px;color:var(--accent);flex-shrink:0;}

.topic-grid{display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(180px,1fr));gap:14px;margin-top:22px;}
.topic-card{position:relative;border-radius:var(--radius);border:1.5px solid var(--border);background:var(--panel);padding:18px;cursor:pointer;box-shadow:var(--shadow-sm);transition:border-color .15s, transform .12s;}
.topic-card:hover{border-color:var(--accent);transform:translateY(-2px);}
.topic-card .num{font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:12px;font-weight:600;color:var(--accent);background:var(--accent-2);display:inline-block;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;margin-bottom:10px;}
.topic-card .title{font-weight:700;font-size:15.5px;}
.topic-card .del-x{position:absolute;top:10px;right:10px;width:24px;height:24px;border-radius:50%;background:var(--panel);border:1.5px solid var(--border);display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:13px;color:var(--ink-dim);cursor:pointer;}
.topic-card .del-x:hover{border-color:var(--danger);color:var(--danger);}
.add-tile{border:2px dashed var(--border);background:transparent;box-shadow:none;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700;color:var(--accent);font-size:14px;}
.add-tile:hover{border-color:var(--accent);}

.page-tabs{display:flex;gap:8px;margin:20px 0;flex-wrap:wrap;}
.page-tab{font-size:14.5px;font-weight:700;padding:10px 18px;border-radius:var(--radius-sm);border:1.5px solid var(--border);cursor:pointer;color:var(--ink-dim);background:var(--panel);transition:all .15s;}
.page-tab.active{background:var(--accent);color:#fff;border-color:var(--accent);}

.page-panel{background:var(--panel);border:1.5px solid var(--border);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:32px 32px;line-height:1.85;min-height:120px;font-size:21px;box-shadow:var(--shadow-sm);color:var(--ink);}
.page-panel .page-label{font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:12px;letter-spacing:.08em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--accent);margin-bottom:16px;font-weight:600;}
.empty-hint{color:var(--ink-dim);font-style:italic;font-size:16px;}
.line{margin-bottom:16px;padding:6px 8px;border-radius:8px;transition:background .3s, box-shadow .3s;}
.line.active-line{background:var(--accent-2);box-shadow:0 0 0 2px var(--accent) inset;}
.editable-active{outline:none;background:var(--accent-2);border-radius:8px;padding:6px 10px;display:block;width:100%;}
.char-name{font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-weight:700;color:var(--teal);margin-right:6px;}
.edit-row{display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:flex-start;margin-bottom:10px;}
.edit-row textarea{flex:1;min-height:60px;}
.char-input{width:100px;font-size:14px;padding:8px 10px;}
.remove-line{width:30px;height:30px;flex-shrink:0;border-radius:8px;border:1.5px solid var(--border);background:var(--panel);color:var(--ink-dim);cursor:pointer;}
.remove-line:hover{border-color:var(--danger);color:var(--danger);}
.add-line-btn{margin-top:6px;}

.toolbar{display:flex;gap:10px;align-items:center;margin-top:18px;flex-wrap:wrap;background:var(--panel-2);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:12px 14px;}
.toolbar .spacer{flex:1;}
.tool-btn{display:flex;align-items:center;gap:7px;padding:9px 15px;border-radius:var(--radius-sm);border:1.5px solid var(--border);background:var(--panel);color:var(--ink);cursor:pointer;font-size:14px;font-weight:600;font-family:'Inter',sans-serif;transition:all .15s;}
.tool-btn:hover{border-color:var(--accent);}
.tool-btn.active{background:var(--accent);color:#fff;border-color:var(--accent);}

.waveform{display:flex;gap:2.5px;align-items:center;height:22px;}
.bar{width:3px;background:var(--accent);border-radius:2px;transition:height .1s;min-height:3px;}

.transcript-box{margin-top:14px;padding:16px 18px;background:var(--panel-2);border-radius:var(--radius);font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-dim);display:none;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.7;}
.transcript-box.show{display:block;}

.qa-item{background:var(--panel);border:1.5px solid var(--border);border-left:4px solid var(--teal);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:26px 28px;margin-bottom:16px;box-shadow:var(--shadow-sm);transition:box-shadow .3s;}
.qa-item.active-line{box-shadow:0 0 0 2px var(--accent);}
.qa-q{font-weight:800;margin-bottom:14px;font-size:22px;color:var(--ink);}
.qa-a{color:var(--ink);line-height:1.85;font-size:20px;margin-bottom:16px;}

.modal-backdrop{position:fixed;inset:0;background:rgba(27,35,64,0.45);display:none;align-items:center;justify-content:center;z-index:50;padding:20px;}
.modal-backdrop.show{display:flex;}
.modal{background:var(--panel);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:26px;max-width:480px;width:100%;box-shadow:var(--shadow);max-height:85vh;overflow-y:auto;}
textarea,input[type=text]{width:100%;background:var(--bg);border:1.5px solid var(--border);color:var(--ink);border-radius:var(--radius-sm);padding:11px 13px;font-family:'Inter',sans-serif;font-size:15px;margin-top:8px;resize:vertical;}
label.field-label{font-size:13px;font-weight:600;color:var(--ink-dim);margin-top:14px;display:block;}

.nav-row{display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;margin-bottom:18px;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap;}
.back-link{font-size:14.5px;font-weight:700;color:var(--ink-dim);cursor:pointer;display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:6px;padding:9px 16px;border-radius:var(--radius-sm);border:1.5px solid var(--border);background:var(--panel);transition:all .15s;}
.back-link:hover{color:var(--accent);border-color:var(--accent);}

.top-bar{display:flex;justify-content:flex-end;gap:8px;margin-bottom:14px;}
.top-bar-btn{font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:12.5px;font-weight:600;color:var(--ink-dim);cursor:pointer;padding:7px 12px;border-radius:var(--radius-sm);border:1.5px solid var(--border);background:var(--panel);transition:all .15s;}
.top-bar-btn.active,.top-bar-btn:hover{color:var(--accent);border-color:var(--accent);}

.fullscreen-mode #app{max-width:960px;}
.fullscreen-mode .page-panel{font-size:24px;padding:48px 52px;}
.fullscreen-mode .qa-item{padding:36px 38px;}
.fullscreen-mode .qa-q{font-size:26px;}
.fullscreen-mode .qa-a{font-size:21px;}
.fullscreen-mode h1{font-size:40px;}
.fullscreen-mode .tool-btn{font-size:16px;padding:12px 20px;}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div id="app"></div>

<div class="modal-backdrop" id="confirmModal">
  <div class="modal">
    <h3 id="confirmText" style="font-size:19px;">Are you sure you want to delete this?</h3>
    <p style="color:var(--ink-dim);font-size:14.5px;margin-top:8px;">This can't be undone.</p>
    <div class="btn-row">
      <button class="btn btn-danger" id="confirmYes">Yes, delete</button>
      <button class="btn btn-ghost" id="confirmNo">Cancel</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="modal-backdrop" id="addModal">
  <div class="modal">
    <h3 style="font-size:19px;">Add a question</h3>
    <input type="text" id="newQ" placeholder="Question">
    <textarea id="newA" rows="4" placeholder="Your answer"></textarea>
    <div class="btn-row">
      <button class="btn btn-primary" id="saveNewQ">Save</button>
      <button class="btn btn-ghost" id="cancelNewQ">Cancel</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="modal-backdrop" id="addTopicModal">
  <div class="modal">
    <h3 style="font-size:19px;">Add a topic</h3>
    <label class="field-label">Title (English)</label>
    <input type="text" id="newTopicEnTitle" placeholder="e.g. Overcoming a setback">
    <label class="field-label">Title (German) — optional, can add later</label>
    <input type="text" id="newTopicDeTitle" placeholder="optional">
    <div class="btn-row">
      <button class="btn btn-primary" id="saveNewTopic">Create topic</button>
      <button class="btn btn-ghost" id="cancelNewTopic">Cancel</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
// ---------------- STATE ----------------
let lang = 'en';
let route = 'lang-select';
let currentPage = 0;
let currentTopicIndex = 0;
let editMode = false;
let editDraft = null;
let wakeLock = null;
let pendingDelete = null;

const T = {
  en:{
    chooseLang:"Choose your language", english:"English", german:"Deutsch",
    whatPractice:"What do you want to practice?", interview:"Interview Practice", stories:"Stories",
    interviewSub:"Your real answers, ready to practice out loud", storiesSub:"Career and self-development stories",
    back:"Back", topics:"Topics", addQuestion:"+ Add question", addTopic:"+ Add topic",
    idea:"Idea", story:"Story", dialogue:"Dialogue",
    edit:"Edit", save:"Save", cancel:"Cancel", loop:"Loop", play:"Play", pause:"Pause", stop:"Stop",
    transcript:"Transcript", delete:"Delete", fullscreen:"Full screen", exitFullscreen:"Exit full screen",
    addParagraph:"+ Add paragraph", addLine:"+ Add line", empty:"No content yet. Click Edit to add some.",
    you:"(you)"
  },
  de:{
    chooseLang:"Wähle deine Sprache", english:"Englisch", german:"Deutsch",
    whatPractice:"Was möchtest du üben?", interview:"Interview-Übung", stories:"Geschichten",
    interviewSub:"Deine echten Antworten, laut zum Üben", storiesSub:"Karriere- und Selbstentwicklungs-Geschichten",
    back:"Zurück", topics:"Themen", addQuestion:"+ Frage hinzufügen", addTopic:"+ Thema hinzufügen",
    idea:"Idee", story:"Geschichte", dialogue:"Dialog",
    edit:"Bearbeiten", save:"Speichern", cancel:"Abbrechen", loop:"Wiederholen", play:"Abspielen", pause:"Pause", stop:"Stopp",
    transcript:"Transkript", delete:"Löschen", fullscreen:"Vollbild", exitFullscreen:"Vollbild beenden",
    addParagraph:"+ Absatz hinzufügen", addLine:"+ Zeile hinzufügen", empty:"Noch kein Inhalt. Klicke auf Bearbeiten.",
    you:"(du)"
  }
};

const topicsDefault = [
{
  en:{
    title:"Self-Learning",
    idea:[
      `Self-learning — it's a strange skill, because nobody really teaches you how to do it. Think about it. School teaches you facts. School teaches you how to pass a test. But it almost never teaches you how to sit alone with something you don't understand... and just stay there, until you do. That part, you have to figure out on your own.`,
      `And here's what's interesting. The people who end up ahead in their careers, in their lives really — it's rarely the ones who knew the most starting out. It's the ones who got comfortable not knowing. Who could look at a gap in their skills and think, "okay... I don't know this yet," instead of "I'll never be good at this." That one shift in language — yet — changes everything.`,
      `Self-learning also means something else, something people don't talk about enough. It means being your own teacher, and your own student, at the same time. Which sounds simple. But it's actually really hard, because a teacher pushes you. A teacher doesn't let you quit when it gets boring, or slow, or frustrating. So when you're teaching yourself... you have to build that discipline internally. Nobody's coming to check on you.`,
      `And I think that's really the core of it. Self-learning isn't really about intelligence. It's about tolerance — tolerance for confusion, tolerance for being bad at something before you're good at it. The people who master this skill, they're not smarter than everyone else. They've just made peace with the uncomfortable part. The part in the middle, where you don't know enough yet, but you're not new anymore either. That's where real growth actually happens.`
    ],
    story:[
      `You know, one of the things I actually know about myself — I learn very fast, especially when I feel challenged. That's honestly what gets the best out of me. And I remember, when I first joined BluePrint Technologies, everything was new to me. I knew nothing about the technology we were selling, nothing about the SAP landscape, which, if you know anything about it, requires a lot of technical knowledge. I also had no idea about the Gulf market. No contacts there. I had never sold enterprise software in my life. And on top of all that... I didn't get any real training. No proper onboarding.`,
      `So here I was. I knew nothing about the product. I had a lack of resources, a lack of support. And I was still expected to hit my monthly target. But instead of letting that overwhelm me, I decided to challenge myself in it. I started asking my manager for direction, for guidance on what to actually study. And I committed to reading two hours a day, every day. On top of that, I dedicated fifteen to twenty minutes daily just recording myself, summarizing what I'd learned that day, out loud. Not for anyone else. Just so I could get comfortable, get structured, in how I explained the products.`,
      `It was a difficult time, honestly. But I kept challenging myself through it. I believed in myself, even when there wasn't a lot of evidence yet to justify that belief. And within a few weeks... something shifted. I was comfortable with our products. I could explain them like an expert, like a senior executive would. And slowly, I started developing my own best practices for building a pipeline — a lot of trial and error, especially with the CRM system we were using, which, by the way, was also completely new to me.`,
      `A few more weeks after that, I was building real pipelines. Generating real, qualified meetings. A twenty percent conversion rate. And eventually, that same drive led me to build Spark2 — the sales intelligence tool that automated a lot of the manual work and increased our numbers significantly. And I think that tells you something. I wasn't just surviving in this new journey. I became a game changer. Someone who changed a company's culture, changed the way they did things, and added real, measurable value.`
    ],
    dialogue:[]
  },
  de:{
    title:"Selbstlernen",
    idea:[],
    story:[],
    dialogue:[]
  }
}
];

const interviewDefault = [
{en:{q:"Tell me about yourself", a:"My name is Ahmed Kamel and I have been in B2B and B2C sales for about 8 years. I started at Vodafone Ireland as a senior telesales advisor in a high volume calls environment where I worked on all kinds of campaigns, inbound and outbound, cold calling, existing customers, and that environment taught me to listen carefully and build trust fast, turning a no into a future yes. I challenged myself on every single call which made me a consistent top performer, ahead of my team members. I spent five years there and stepped up as acting team lead for two of those years managing 15 people. I learned German during that time which led to a role at Transcom handling German-speaking accounts. After that I ran the operations team and built the entire workflow from scratch at El Meraki, then moved to BluePrint Technologies, an SAP Gold Partner, where I own the Gulf territory building pipelines across KSA, UAE, and Kuwait. I also built a sales intelligence tool called Spark2 that increased our qualified meetings seven times."},
 de:{q:"Erzähl mir etwas über dich", a:"Mein Name ist Ahmed Kamel. Ich arbeite seit etwa acht Jahren im Kundenservice und im Telefonverkauf. Im Jahr 2018 habe ich als englischsprachiger Telefonverkäufer bei Vodafone Ireland angefangen. In dieser Stelle habe ich viele Fähigkeiten weiterentwickelt. Zum Beispiel: Wie geht man mit Kunden um? Wie baut man schnell Vertrauen auf? Und am meisten habe ich gelernt, wirklich zuzuhören, um die Probleme der Kunden zu verstehen und eine passende Lösung anzubieten. Während dieser Zeit habe ich Deutsch gelernt. Das hat mir eine Stelle als deutschsprachiger Kundenbetreuer bei Transcom ermöglicht. Dort habe ich meine Sprache viel verbessert. Ich war dafür verantwortlich, Lieferprobleme für Kunden zu lösen. Zurzeit arbeite ich als Lead Generation Specialist bei BluePrint Technologies, einem SAP Gold Partner. Ich bin dafür verantwortlich, neue interessierte Kunden in der Golfregion zu finden. Außerdem baue ich langfristige Beziehungen zu Kunden auf und pflege diese Beziehungen weiter."}},
{en:{q:"Explain what Deel does", a:"So Deel basically solves a problem that every growing company hits at some point, you find the right person for the job but they are in a different country and suddenly you are dealing with local contracts, local payroll, taxes, equipment shipping, visas. It becomes a whole project just to hire one person. What Deel did is take all of that and put it in one platform. You decide to hire someone today, they are onboarded, contracted, and ready to go the same day, paid in their local currency, with their laptop shipped to their door. They have five modules, payroll, HR, IT, benefits, hiring, even visa and mobility, and they all talk to each other. So instead of using five different vendors and hoping everything connects, you have one system, one dashboard, one team to call. 40,000 companies use them including LinkedIn, Canva, H&M, Puma. That tells you this is not a niche product anymore, this is infrastructure for how modern companies hire."},
 de:{q:"", a:""}},
{en:{q:"Why this role / why Deel", a:"This role is the natural next step from where I am. I have spent two years building pipelines, managing CRM systems, and coordinating across Gulf markets. I have proven I can generate results in complex environments. Now I want to work in a bigger role where I can go deeper, own more of the outcome, and be surrounded by people with more experience who push me to reach my potential, and in return I bring eight years of sales discipline, a Gulf market that I know from the inside, and a proven ability to build pipelines and deliver results from the first month."},
 de:{q:"", a:""}},
{en:{q:"Biggest strength", a:"My biggest strength is that I build solutions instead of waiting for them. At BluePrint I was frustrated with how long manual prospect research was taking, 20 to 30 minutes per account, just to understand the customer's situation before reaching out. So I built a sales intelligence tool from scratch, no budget, no team, just me and the problem. One month later it was running live, increasing our qualified meetings seven times. At El Meraki there was no system for running operations, so I built one from scratch, they are still using it today to manage customers data and track inventory. But I am not just a builder, I am a salesperson first. Eight years across B2B and B2C taught me to build trust, handle all kinds of objections, and drive revenue. That combination is what I bring to every role."},
 de:{q:"", a:""}},
{en:{q:"Biggest weakness", a:"Early in my career at Vodafone, my weakness was trying to close too early in the call, before the customer shows clear signs of interest. I believe that I lost a few sales I could have closed if I was more patient and listened more carefully instead of pushing toward the close too early. My manager noticed this and flagged it and advised me to sit and listen to some of the top performers' calls. That's exactly how I learned to actually listen to the objections carefully and handle them before rushing toward the end, and also to recognize the right moment to close instead of forcing it before the customer is ready."},
 de:{q:"", a:""}},
{en:{q:"Biggest challenge you faced", a:"The biggest challenge I faced was early in my career at Vodafone Ireland. I was new in a high volume environment with experienced people around me, I did not accept the gap between me and the top achievers. I went to my manager and asked to sit beside one of the top achievers in the team to learn from them. I listened to every call, studied how they handled objections, how they built trust in the first thirty seconds, and how they turned a no into a real conversation. I applied everything I learned on my calls. Slowly the gap closed and then I was the one ahead, consistent top performer, and eventually acting team lead. That same determination followed me to BluePrint Technologies. I walked into the SAP world knowing nothing about the landscape, with a Gulf territory and no existing pipeline. I built it from scratch. But what really changed the game was when I realized our outreach process was costing us time we did not have. So I built a sales CRM tool completely on my own, no budget, no team. One month later it was live increasing our qualified meetings seven times."},
 de:{q:"", a:""}},
{en:{q:"Proudest achievement", a:"My proudest achievement is not one moment, it is a pattern that has repeated itself throughout my career. At Vodafone Ireland I was not the most experienced person on the team, but I became a consistent top performer because I listened more carefully than anyone else and refused to give up on an objection. That is what led me to step up as acting team lead, not a title, not seniority, just results. Then I decided to learn German from scratch, the determination is what kept me going. That opened a completely different market and a completely different level of exposure. When I moved into the SAP world I knew nothing about the landscape, I had never sold enterprise software. Within months I was building pipelines and generating qualified leads across KSA, UAE, and Kuwait. And when the tools we had were not good enough, I built my own, a sales CRM tool completely independently that automated our outreach and increased our qualified meetings seven times."},
 de:{q:"", a:""}},
{en:{q:"How do you research a prospect before reaching out?", a:"Before reaching out to any prospect I want to know a few things, what their business actually does and how it makes money, what business challenges they have now and what is their SAP landscape, and who the right person to contact is. I use LinkedIn Sales Navigator for stakeholder mapping, company news and job postings for timing signals, and whatever public information exists about their technology or operational setup."},
 de:{q:"", a:""}},
{en:{q:"Why do you want to leave your current role?", a:"BluePrint gave me real B2B sales experience in complex Gulf markets, and I'm grateful for that. But I'm not just looking for any next role, I'm specific about why Deel, you're one of the fastest-growing companies in this space, scaling fast, targeting an IPO, and that creates a different kind of learning and career growth environment. What excites me also about this specific role is that the actual work is the same as what I do, building pipelines and generating qualified meetings in the same Gulf market I already know. So it's not just the company's growth I'm chasing, it's that I already enjoy this exact work, and I believe I will be successful at it."},
 de:{q:"", a:""}},
{en:{q:"How do you build a prospect list from scratch?", a:"I always start with the ICP, what does the perfect customer look like? Industry, company size, geography, likely pain points, likely decision-maker titles. Once the ICP is precise, building the list becomes easy using the right tools. LinkedIn Sales Navigator for company identification and stakeholder mapping. Apollo and Lusha for contact data extraction."},
 de:{q:"", a:""}},
{en:{q:"The right time to close", a:"The right time to close is when the customer shows real buying signals. I listen carefully and handle objections first, but I'm watching for specific signs: they ask about price, delivery, or how something practical would actually work for them. That shows me they already picture themselves using it. Other signs are things like repeating back what I said in their own words. It's different with warm or inbound leads, those customers already arrived with the intention to buy. I don't spend time over-explaining features or wait for the same signals, I close early with them because waiting in that case might just complicate things."},
 de:{q:"", a:""}},
